<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=978734872478></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f978734872478><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=6&mid=978734872478>Paladin Tricks Not Everyone Knows</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=6&mid=978734872478#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=17094><span id=Sage>Kneesmasher</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>397 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Jan 5th 10:49 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I wanted to post some tricks of the trade I have learned and that have saved my hide repeatedly during my previous 27 lvls running mostly solo as a Dwarven Paladin.&nbsp;&nbsp;In my travels I have found not everyone knows these tricks and perhaps this will start discussion that will lead to others sharing what they've learned.<br><br>1) The use of Flash of Light (FOL) as a life saving spell. I do not have confirmation but it has been my observations that, for the most part, creatures you blind tend to hit for less damage on average while blinded. That's not to say they don't land some good shots, but on average the damage is lowerm sometimes MUCH lower.  This is a great benefit in and of itself and most players know that FOL also works as a GREAT taunt even on those beasts that are stubborn.  If the beast won't turn from your Caster, hit him with a FOL. It usually works well.  But what I have found is that many players do NOT know the other FOL benefit. In combat, you can blind a Mob, step back away from it, and it will run away from you!! This can be a major benefit giving you time to run to zone, heal up, fight another mob, cast a root, change weapons, or whatever. Keep in mind there is a down side in that the Mob will return and may bring friends when he does, especially in a dungeon setting as opposed to open outdoors, but if you can root him after he runs off you can buy even more time.  Try it, it's a nifty trick when running solo. It takes a bit of practice but could save your life.<br><br>2) The use of Center as a heal instead of just a buff.  Until you reach 30th lvl you are pretty much saddled with two regular heal spells, minor heal and light heal.  If you have the time and don't mind the repetition, minor heal is actually a more efficient heal than light heal is.  Minor heal gives you 1pt of health for 1pt of mana used.  Light heal gives you 20 hps for 25 pts of mana and is therefore less efficient at converting mana into hit points. However, while the 22nd lvl Paladin spell "Center" is traditionally considered a buff, I have found that many Paladins don't realize it is even more efficient at healing than either of the other two!  When you cast Center, you get over 50 hps for only 40 mana!! Granted it takes time to throw and if you are in a hurry for hps (like when a mob is running away from you because of you FOL!!!!) Light Heal is the way to go, but if you have the time and want to maximize your mana useage, cast Center over and over again and get more bang for the buck!  Also, since Center takes time to recover from once it is thrown, you can cast Center, then as soon as possible cast a Light Heal, and by the time the Light Heal is completed, you are ready to cast Center again! You can transfer mana into hit points quite effectively and quickly this way.<br><br>3) Since Paladins get DD spells against undead, it is possible, although not the most efficient process, to kite undead as a Paladin.  While root is a very unpredictable spell, if you can get a root to hold, you can blast undead with your Ward Undead spell. Also, keep in mind, if you have the room, the range of a Ward Undead spell is long. Make sure you move far enough away and it's quite possible you can reroot the undead Mob before it even gets to you, move away, and nuke again! I've killed undead mobs this way when I was low on hit points, but high on mana.<br><br>Just a few things to think about. Try it for yourself!<br><br>Kneesmasher Ayebulger<br>27th lvl Dwarven Paladin<br>Twilight Brethren<br>&nbsp;<br>Kneesmasher Ayebulger<br>Dwarven Knight<br>Torvonnilous Server<br><br>"Never Mistake Kindness for Weakness"</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
